  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Maria Weston Chapman writes about family business affairs. Chapman says: &quot;I saw by the papers that the row was a very tame affair, looked to me like a wrestling match.&quot; Business is flourishing. &quot;We shall lose about $16000, a flea compared to most people.&quot; An old Scotchman named George Smith, for whom Chapman had invested nearly a million dollars within the month, complimented her on her skillful purchasing; she now has the &quot;whole control of the stock department.&quot; There is no chance of dissolution [of the Union?] just yet. Stocks only rose ten per cent. She contrasts the former attitude of the South with the present; now they must sell at a loss, for they must have dollars to buy food. &quot;I look for insurrection within the month.&quot; She describes the health and beauty of the little boy [perhaps a grandchild] with her.</subfield>
  </datafield>
